name: Orcas Island Skatepark
description: The bowl at this park is on a whole other level. The concrete is super smooth and you can really fly around it. It was my first time on real pool ledge and since I had only been back on a skateboard for all of 3 months after an 8 year hiatus I wasn't able to do much. But man was this thing fun to ride. I was there on a Friday afternoon and it was completely empty. Came back on Sunday on the way home at around noon and it was packed full people on the upper deck with about 5 or so riding the shallow end of the bowl.

images.description: enjoi
It was my first time on real pool ledge and it took me a bit to try and axle stall on it.

name: Freedom Park
description: Medium sized bowl with some decent concrete and a nice street section for the younger crowd. I grew up in Mill Creek but unfortunately this park wasn't built until 2004 and by that point I was about to graduate from high school and had stopped actively skating. When I first rode this bowl in the summer of 2007 I had just got back into skating and had only been riding a 2.5 foot mini-ramp I built in my backyard so I wasn't able to fully appreciate this bowl. Then in the summer of 2017 I really got back into skating and was able to appreciate it.

images.description: Really wish this bowl existed 20 years ago.
The deep end.
Got a real nice curve to it.
Street section. Got some nice features, but it all heads in one direction so I imagine traffic jams back in the day must have been frequent.
Why are skateparks always empty now?
A little 2 set.
All going in one direction.
Such a nice bowl.
Took me a couple tries to find a line I liked, but after a while you can start to cruise this thing.

name: Enterprise Skatepark
description: Passed by this skatepark on my way to Lake Wallowa to do some fishing and decided to stop and do a few drop ins. Obviously not the greatest skatepark but it sure as hell beats nothing. I get the feeling that it's mostly used by BMX bikers.

images.description: The entire skatepark.
Two metal quarter pipes and a funky metal pyramid that isn't really a pyramid. Is it a fun box?
Artsy photo.

name: Adams Skatepark
description: A small little skatepark in the middle of nowhere Oregon. While not the greatest it still beats what I had in my neighborhood growing up which was nothing. The quarter pipe leaves much to be desired but the street elements are definitely skateable and enjoyable.

images.description: Look at all that wax. My sweet Del Sol in the distance.
It's got 1 quarter pipe with concrete that was shaped into a "coping".
For being such a small town it's nice to see a park here.
Banked mini-ramp thingy.
Got a nice little ledge/manny pad and a 4 stair with a rail.
enjoi
I'm guessing someone's dad owns a concrete mixer and donated his time and supplies.

name: Jefferson Park
description: This bowl is deep and it's got the best views in the city. The deep end of this bowl is definitely beyond my abilities but the shallow end is fun to rip around. When I was here on a Saturday around noon I only had to share the bowl with 2 other people.

images.description: Just look at that view.
A bowl with a view.
Nice and deep.
It's got a nice little mini-ramp section with a spine.
Jefferson park is just all around awesome.

name: Judkins Park
description: The snake run here is a blast but watch out for the bowl at the end it's tight. It's got a street section but I stuck to the snake run. Due to it's size it doesn't take a lot of people to make this place feel packed.

images.description: Snake run.
Super tight bowl.

name: Delridge Park
description: Your choice of a bowl or a classic pool. The bowl is definitely in contention for the best within the city of Seattle. It's got so much flow and is tons of fun to just pump around. The street section is layed out in a snake run type of format - a really nice design.

images.description: A huge pool with lots of awesome shade.
Pool ledge.
Another pool shot.
This thing is big.

name: Roxhill Park
description: A fun a little skatepark. But not much here if you're not a street skater. A typical entry-level neighborhood type of skatepark that is easily overrun by scootet kids.

images.description: A nice little street park.
Lots of street features. But only 1 quarter pipe.
Also packed full of kids on scooters.

name: Crossroads Community Center
description: A nice big bowl. My only complaint is that it all slopes down to the deep end so it can be hard for a person new to bowl skating (me) to make it back up to the shallow end while still carrying much speed.

images.description: This bowl has a natural slope down into the deep end.
Lots of "steep drop off" warnings all around.

Lots of fun to be had, but not really for beginners.

Oyster dome in black and white.

name: 'Full Pipe' Skatepark
description: This park has got a lot going on. The 'S' shaped bowl here is huge and can't wait to get back here when I'm good enough to actually enjoy it. I would highly recomment a helmet if you want to skate this thing. The kidney pool is super steep with out much flat bottom. The street section is small but has some nice features.

images.description: Tight and deep pool.

name: 'Old Clover Bowl' Skatepark
description: A crusty old park that really shows its age. The coping was literally been bashed in on half of the deep end.

name: Seatac Community Center Skatepark
description: A nice fun little park that was empty on a Saturday around noon. Not a lot for an old bowl rider like myself but there was a mini-ramp to mess around on.

images.description: Standard street features, good for the youth.

name: River City Skatepark
description: With the way its laid out in a circle you can literally pump around and around and around. No coping but the ledges are pretty waxed up in sections.

images.description: Interesting park layout.

The parking isn't the best, but I would skate here again for sure.

name: Dan Dever Memorial Skatepark
description: I was headed over to Wallowa Lake in Eastern Oregon to go fishing for Father's Day weekend and found this park when I stopped to grab some food in Othello. It's definitely a gem in a the middle of nowhere. The kids to get to grow up riding this don't know how lucky they are.

images.description: I really enjoyed skating this park.
A nice brand new park.

Kinked rail.

The double stair set would have been awesome in my younger years.

name: Gig Harbor Skatepark
description: I really got the feeling that this park was designed by someone who's kids skated or something. It has a lot of random unconnected features seemingly tossed about. But the deep mini-ramp is pretty sweet.

images.description: Snake run.
This bowl would be awesome if it was more enclosed.

name: Wenatchee Skatepark
description: By it's design this park feels older than it actually is. There is no coping, nor any ledge, it's all roll in around the entire park. There was one fidget spinner looking element that had been waxed up, but that was about it for grinding.

images.description: This bowl was completely unskateable. It wasn't even a bowl as so much an inverted pyramid. Sidewalls where chunky and clearly not designed or poured by anyone that cared. The artwork was nice though.
Who the hell builds a skatepark with no coping?
The best feature in the entire park. The fidget spinner was fun to mess around on as it was coated in wax making it the only grind-able element in the entire park.

name: Walter Hall Park
description: Definitely showing it's age. I seriously used to have to wake up at 6 am on a Saturday to make it here before the crowds when I was 14. Now I show up on Saturday at 5 pm and there were less than 3 kids actually skating.

images.description: I grew up on that rail. So many awesome board slides.
Nice deep bowl.

I remember when I use to have to wake up at 6:00 am on a Saturday to get here before 7:00 am so we could get a solid hour in before the huge crowds showed up. No one was here on a Saturday at around 5:00 pm now.

name: South Whidbey Park
description: Something for the whole family. Only complaint I can make is I wish there was something like a giant quater pipe on the open end to connect it all together. But you can get some decent speed crusing this place. Plus there's a giant 'Castle Park' along with play fields so there is something for everyone here. A great addition to the South End.
